                    <history>
                        <origin>
                            <p>
                                <origPlace>
                                    <placeName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/place/100104">Germany</placeName>
                                    <placeName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/place/100224">Erfurt</placeName>
                                </origPlace>, <origDate notAfter="1439" notBefore="1414">1414 and 1439?</origDate>. The manuscript contains two colophons, one placing unit 1 in <placeName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/place/100224">Erfurt</placeName>, <placeName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/place/100104">Germany</placeName>, in <date when="1414"/> (<locus from="62r" to="62r" scheme="folios"/>), and one dating unit 3 to <date when="1439"/> (<locus from="91r" to="91r" scheme="folios"/>). The second colophon appears, however, to be a later addition. The hand has, furthermore, corrected the date from <date when="1459"/> to -39. All three watermarks found in the respective units can be dated to <date from="1408" to="1415">1408–15</date>, matching the date of the first colophon, and all three are found in <placeName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/place/100355">Rothenburg ob der Tauber</placeName>
                            </p>
                        </origin>
                        <provenance>
                            <p>A 200 once made up one of the halves of a single manuscript - the second half of which now constitutes no. 400 of <orgName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/org/100178">Växjö stiftsbibliotek</orgName> (formerly Kungliga gymnasi biblioteket) - which hails from the <orgName>Carthusian charterhouse of Salvatorberg in Erfurt</orgName>; it is listed in their library catalogue as <quote>112.2</quote> (<bibl>
                                    <title type="short" ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/bibl/107421">Lehmann (1935)</title>
                                    <citedRange from="8" to="8" unit="page"/>
                                </bibl>). A former librarian notes that the <placeName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/place/100122">Växjö</placeName> manuscript (no. 400) retains the original binding, which carries the Carthusian signum as well as a note on the purchase of the manuscript by <persName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/person/101069">George Stephens</persName> from a <quote>Hr Schmidt, Bookseller</quote> in <placeName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/place/100284">Halle</placeName> in <date when="1848"/>.</p>
                        </provenance>
                        <provenance>
                            <p>The original manuscript appears to have been intact when it was sold at auction in <date when="1836"/> as part of the library of book collector <persName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/person/102541">Friedrich Gottlieb Julius von Bülow</persName> (<bibl>
                                    <title type="short" ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/bibl/107430">Schäffer (1836)</title>
                                    <citedRange from="32" to="32" unit="page"/>
                                    <citedRange from="379" to="379" unit="number"/>
                                </bibl>). Presumably, it had come into <persName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/person/102541">von Bülow's</persName> possession earlier in the 19th century, when the charterhouse of Salvatorberg was secularized.</p>
                        </provenance>
                        <acquisition>
                            <p>Purchased from <persName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/person/101069">George Stephens</persName> in <date when="1848"/> (see note on <locus from="L1r" to="L1r" scheme="folios"/>).</p>
                        </acquisition>
                    </history>
